      " "
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "p",
      null,
      "By default, when an app is viewed in the browser, Ionic will apply the ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "md"
      ],
      " mode. However, since Ionic components adapt according to their platform, it is helpful to be able to view what the app will look like on iOS. To do this, add ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "?ionic:mode=ios"
      ],
      " to the URL where the app is being served. For example, if the app is served on port ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "8100"
      ],
      ", the url would be: ",
      [
        "code",
        null,
        "http://localhost:8100/?ionic:mode=ios"
      ],
      "."
    ],
    " ",
    [
      "blockquote",
      null,
      " ",
      [
        "p",
        null,
        "This will not change which platform the browser sees being used. The platform is determined by device detection and inspecting the user-agent. To change the platform, the user-agent must be changed. To do this, open up Chrome DevTools with ",
        [
          "kbd",
          null,
          "Ctrl+Shift+I"
        ],
        "(",
        [
          "kbd",
          null,
          "Cmd+Option+I"
        ],
        " on Mac), and then toggle device mode on with ",
        [
          "kbd",
          null,
          "Ctrl+Shift+M"
        ],
        "(",
        [
          "kbd",
          null,
          "Cmd+Option+M"
        ],
        " on Mac)."
